explanation:
For checking for unreachable code in OS_TaskDelete_Impl you need the definitions or semantics of all symbols that affect control flow or could forcibly short-circuit/alter execution so that a branch can never be taken. Short reasons for each: 

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro that obtains the impl record from the token. If this macro expands to code that can e.g. assert/return/abort, it could make the rest of the function unreachable; its expansion also determines how impl is computed.

- OS_impl_task_table: The object table used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to understand how impl is derived (e.g. can it produce a compile-time constant or cause early exit).

- OS_impl_task_internal_record_t: Structure type of impl; required to know the member types (impl->id) and whether accessing impl->id has side-effects or is valid (could be a macro that changes behavior).

- OS_object_token_t: The token type passed in; needed to know whether token can encode values that make OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET/Index macros behave in a way that makes code unreachable.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: The static call graph indicates index-from-token helpers may be involved (OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET often expands to use this); its implementation could perform checks or fail paths that affect reachability.

- pthread_cancel: The return values and whether this function is modeled/overridden in the project matter. If it is a wrapper that always returns a fixed value or always aborts/longjmps, branches could be unreachable. Need its signature/semantics to know if both (ret != 0) and (ret == 0) paths are possible.

- pthread_join: Similar to pthread_cancel — its behavior/override could make subsequent code unreachable or always produce certain return codes; also needed to see if it can block or terminate the process.

- OS_DEBUG: Usually a logging macro; if it expands to code that does more (e.g. longjmp/exit/return), it could render following code unreachable. Must know its expansion/behavior.

- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: Called within the debug print; if it has side effects that affect control flow or can abort, it may alter reachability of debug paths.

- OS_ObjectIdToInteger: Used in debug formatting; if it can abort or have other side effects, it could affect reachability of the debug branch.

- strerror: Standard libc function used to format error text; if replaced/overridden in the project with non-standard behavior it could affect reachability of debug branch.

- OS_SUCCESS: The function always returns this constant; need its definition to ensure the function does not contain a subsequent unreachable return or different control-flow expectations (e.g. if defined as an expression with side effects).

Providing these symbols (definitions/headers/implementations) lets an analyzer determine whether any branch in OS_TaskDelete_Impl is impossible to reach (for example because a called macro always aborts or a called function is a project-local wrapper that always returns a fixed value), thus answering the MISRA C unreachable-code question.
